ious reviews. The review begins by introducing the reader to over-arching principles that are needed to investigate biomineralization phenomena and shows the current state of knowledge regarding the major approaches to mineralization that organisms have developed over the course of Earth history. By exploring the complexities that underlie the "synthesis" of biogenic materials, and therefore the basis for how compositions and structures of biominerals are mediated (or not), we believe this volume will be instrumental in propelling studies of biomineralization to a new level of research questions that are grounded in an understanding of the underlying biological phenomena.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAufsatzsammlung. 4aBiogeochemie. 4aBiomineralisation. 4aMineralogie. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Mineralogy.2bisacsh1 aBazylinski, Dennis A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Anne L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Yoreo, James J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Yoreo, James J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDove, Patricia M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDove, Patricia M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErez, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, John S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrankel, Richard B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHenriksen, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnoll, Andrew H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcConnaughey, Ted A., econtributor.4c